[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: Overarching Concept - The Bluff!"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/m5Dh3tlz"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "Overarching Concept - The Bluff!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/89IpKSiD"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1pp3bp/p2p2p1/2nPpp1n/2P1P3/2N1BP2/PPBQ2PP/1K1R2NR b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

{ This is a concept that applies to multiple of the sacrifices listed in the chapter, and a general psychological trick as well, which I've utilized successfully in my attacks. If you've played poker, it's just like a bluff there. The bluff concept in chess is often portrayed as a mix of overconfidence and deceit. }
1... b5 { The general idea is "I will throw at you this crazy move. You can punish me and accept the consequences or back off and I get the benefits". In this position, Black would love to play b5 without hanging the pawn. So instead of playing slow with Rb8, Black bluffs with b5 immediately. See the first sacrifice below for details } *


