[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 1) Benko Gambit style"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/w2OZCtFC"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "1) Benko Gambit style"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/kzRryo14"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1pp3bp/p2p2p1/2nPpp1n/2P1P3/2N1BP2/PPBQ2PP/1K1R2NR b - - 5 12"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

{ As soon as you see the kings castled opposite sides, two important concepts should come to mind:
1) Pawn Breaks
2) Time
Black ideally should try to play for b5 safely, but a preparation move like Rb8 fails to b4, when the knight sadly has to retreat, nearly ending all of Black's queenside chances. }
12... b5! { Black wastes no time and goes for the immediate b5. This move acts as a bluff. If White is bold and accepts the gambit, Black will have tons of play on the now open a and b files. If White cowards out and declines, Black has no gotten b5 in for free. So, win win. } (12... Rb8? { Too slow! } 13. b4) 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Ba6 { With loads of compensation and a great attack. See https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1480587 for a top Grandmaster game from this position. } *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 2) Greek Gift"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/D6s4j08x"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "2) Greek Gift"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/gP7axRtS"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pppn1ppp/4p3/3pP3/1b1P4/2NB1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 5 7"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

{ Probably the most common sacrifice at the amateur rank. This bishop sacrifice against the castled king destroys the enemy king safety and allows quick invasion of your knight and queen. The majority of the successful Greek Gifts requires your pawn on e5 to prevent your opponent from playing Nf6 }
7. Bxh7+ Kxh7 8. Ng5+ Kg8 (8... Kg6 9. h4 { Threatening h5+, and the black king has nowhere to go. } 9... f5 10. h5+ Kh6 11. Nxe6+) 9. Qh5 Re8 { Attempting to flee with the king } 10. Qxf7+ Kh8 11. Qh5+ Kg8 12. Qh7+ Kf8 13. Qh8+ Ke7 14. Qxg7# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 3) Greek Gift using h-file"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/mKdUosUu"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "3) Greek Gift using h-file"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/3vlcrZd3"]
[FEN "rn1q1rk1/pb2bppp/4p3/3pB3/7P/3B1N2/PPP2PP1/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

{ The Greek Gift using the h-file is another common version. This potentially uses the Rook on h1 to contribute to the attack }
1. Bxh7+ Kxh7 2. Ng5+ { Black could capture the knight, but it would allow the rook on h1 to enter the attack, so Black is left with no good choice } 2... Bxg5 3. hxg5+ Kg8 4. Qh5 f6 5. g6! { A must-know pattern. g6 is not a check, but is deadly. It is essential to cut off the Black king's flight square f7 first before Qh8#. Checkmate is unstoppable. } *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 4) Sac the h-pawn to open file"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/XnoSBnGS"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B78"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Dragon Variation, Yugoslav Attack, Old Line"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "4) Sac the h-pawn to open file"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/kSD9XrmV"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. h4 Nc4 (12... h5 { h5 is the main line in the sharp Sicilian Dragon for logical reason: Allowing White to play h5 is simply too dangerous. }) 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. h5! { Sacrificing the h-pawn to open up the h-file with 2 tempi. Again, using the bluff concept. Black accepts the gambit and also the consequences of White's now open h-file. Or else White will play hxg6 anyways } 14... Nxh5 15. g4 Nf6 (15... Ng3? 16. Rhg1 { Knight is trapped here }) 16. Nde2 { Solidifying the center before pursuing the Bh6 kingside attack. } (16. Bh6? { Bh6 right away runs into some problems with the loose Nd4. } 16... Nxe4) *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 5) Rxh5 exchange sac"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/HonvkGxx"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D01"]
[Opening "Rapport-Jobava System"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "5) Rxh5 exchange sac"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/VawrVJnf"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O (5... h5 { Black is advised to play h5 to avoid the onslaught altogether. }) 6. h5 Nxh5 7. Rxh5! gxh5 8. Qxh5 { Although White is down an exchange, this position is arguably already winning for White, with a huge score in practice. All of White's pieces will jump in the attack, while Black's are all in hiding on the back rank. } 8... c6 9. Bd3 f5 10. Nf3 Qe8 11. Qh2 { White will castle long and play Rh1 with a decisive attack. } { [%cal Ge1c1] } *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 6) Sac the g-pawn to open g-file"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/sEz7F5Ck"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D38"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Ragozin Defense"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "6) Sac the g-pawn to open g-file"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/s8pIlytx"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bd2 O-O 7. g4 { If this move seems strangely familiar to you, then you must have watched Carlsen - Giri in the Magnus Carlsen invitational. g4 is a bold move that makes complete sense. White offers the g-pawn in order to gain full control on the g-file for the rook. If Black declines, then g5 to take advatnage of the h6 hook is quite strong. } 7... Nxg4 (7... Nbd7 { If Black declines the gambit, White will get g5 safely and also an open g-file. Lots of fun for White } 8. g5 hxg5 9. Bxg5 { [%cal Gh1g1,Gd1c2] }) 8. Rg1 *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 7) Sac to open up square"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/Jm5HFCTY"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "7) Sac to open up square"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/PVP1z86f"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/1b1nbppp/pn1pp3/1p4P1/3NPP1P/1P1B3R/P1P1NQ2/1KBR4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

1. f5 e5 2. f6! { A great in between move! Your knight is not forced to move just because it's attacked. If that was the case, the knight has nothing better than to just retreat to f3, and Black will continue with his initiative with d5. This in-between move frees up the key square f5 for the knight. A truly smart pawn sacrifice. } 2... gxf6 3. Nf5 { Not only does White achieve the beautiful knight outpost on f5, an attack is quickly forming on the now open g-file. } *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 8) Nd5 sac in Sicilian"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/B1vdFYXw"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "8) Nd5 sac in Sicilian"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/tzwz2GmT"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/1bq2ppp/p2ppn2/1p6/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQR1K1 w kq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

{ This theme is very common in any Open Sicilians. In the majority of these cases, the knight sacrifice is not completely sound. But there is so much compensation that White often scores very well. A computer may defend as Black easily, but for any human player (including GMs), it is quite tough. }
10. a4 { Often common to play Nd5 after black plays b4 for the knight to hit another target. } 10... b4 11. Nd5! { If you haven't seen this sac before, this will look very dubious. It is indeed a long term advantage that White gains. Black more or less has to accept the sacrifice or else the knight will just sit there controlling all sides of the board. } 11... exd5 12. exd5+ Kd8 (12... Be7? 13. Nf5) 13. c3 { Now it is clear why the moves a4 b4 are inserted at the start! White can now create a pawn break on the queenside to open yet another file for a rook, the c-file! Bg5 and Rc1 will complete development while Black is completely tangled up. See https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1513377 for a sample game with the Nd5 sacrifice } *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 9) Sac piece to open adjacent file"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/Ba2LVlAh"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "9) Sac piece to open adjacent file"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/RW3ed2IL"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp2bppp/2bppn2/q5B1/3NPP2/2NQ4/PPP3PP/2KR3R b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

12... h6 13. h4! { Again, we see the bluff concept at play. Black would love to push back the pesky Bg5, and White wants to keep it there. Therefore, h4 is a great move to keep the bishop on g5 and throw out a bluff. If Black dares to capture, the open h-file is quite deadly. Otherwise, White reaps all the benefits.. and more! g4 comes next and a pawn storm is on its way! } 13... Rfc8 { Smart to not accept the sacrifice } (13... hxg5?! 14. hxg5 Ng4 15. e5 g6 16. Qh3) 14. g4! { The threat is now Bxf6 followed by g5 to crack open the kingside. } *


