[FEN "2r3k1/1b2qp2/Bp2pbpp/2rp4/8/P1P1P1NP/1P2QPP1/2KR3R b - - 0 20"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

{ Sacrificing on c3 is so tempting, but it is important to calculate which piece to sacrifice. Turns out it is essential to bring the queen into the attack as soon as possible, so Rxc3+ is the far stronger one. }
20... Rxc3+! 21. bxc3 Qxa3+ { The queen entering the game is the key move. } 22. Kb1 (22. Kd2?? Qxc3#) 22... Rxc3 { Rb3+ is coming up next and there are countless wins from here. } *


[Event "Best Sacrifices to aid Attack: 13) Sacrifice pawn to ensure an open file"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gG3MmNTi/mzoHC7Xr"]
[Date "2020.08.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Top Sacrifices in the Attack"]
[ChapterName "13) Sacrifice pawn to ensure an open file"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZRY61QJ6/W48ffh33"]
[FEN "r2qr1k1/1b2nppp/1pppp3/6PP/1b1PP3/pPN1QP2/P1P5/BK1B2RR w Kq - 10 6"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.08.03"]
[UTCTime "02:16:38"]

{ A very common dilemma when you're in the process of pawn storming: If you play h6, Black locks up the position with g6, and if you play g6, black will play fxg6 hxg6 h6 to close the position. In either situation, White doesn't get a full open file. However, with this sacrificial technique, you can ensure an open file! }
6. g6 fxg6 (6... hxg6 7. hxg6 { If Black plays hxg6, you can just play hxg6 and welcome the open h-file. }) 7. h6! { Now Black cannot play g6 since there is now already a pawn on g6. This technique figuratively takes your g-pawn off the board, which is the purpose of pawn breaks in the first place. } *


